===Etymology===
{{ja-kanjitab|まつ|yomi=k}}
From {{inh|ja|ojp|-|sort=まつ}}. Attested in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712 and the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' of 759.<ref name="KDJ2O">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2 Online|まつ 【松】|lid=200203f17109ZJ6pI9HI}}</ref><ref name="JDB">{{R:JDB|page=681}}</ref> In turn, from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*matu|sort=まつ}}.

Various theories exist regarding its ultimate origin:<ref name="KDJ2O"/>
* Might be a shift from {{m|ja|保つ|tr=tamotsu|t=to hold}}. However, the accent of {{m|ja|保つ|tr=tamotsu}} in the Heian period is <code>HHL</code>, while {{m-self|ja|松|tr=matsu}} is <code>LH</code>. It can be better derived from {{m|ja|持つ|tr=motsu|t=to hold, to carry}}, which has <code>LF</code> accent in the Heian period.
* Might be from {{m|ja|待つ|tr=matsu|t=to wait}}, either from the way that a pine tree must wait for leaves to fall to grow new ones, or from the way that it lasts ten thousand years and preserves its color. The accent of {{m|ja|待つ|tr=matsu}} is <code>LF</code>.
* Possibly derived from {{m|ja|全く|tr=mataku|t=entirely}}, from {{m|ja|全い|tr=matai|t=complete}}, because it spends its time in the snow for winter. However, the classical term {{m|ja|全し|tr=matasi}} is <code>HHF</code> in the Heian period.
* From {{m|ja|睫毛|tr=matsuge|t=eyelashes}}, since their leaves represent such. However, it requires deletion of the ''-ge'', and ''matsuge'' is certainly from {{m|ja|目|tr=ma-|t=eye}}.
* From {{m|ja|真常木|tr=matonoki|t=true eternal tree}}, as the pine tree is an evergreen tree.
* From a place name {{m|ja|3=松のむらたち|tr=MATSU no muratachi}}, as opposed to ''muratatsu''.
* From {{m|ja|芽厚|tr=meatsu|lit=buds (are) thick}}.
* From {{m|ja|纏わる|tr=matsuwaru|t=get wrapped around}}, as the leaves are around the trunk.
* From {{m|ja|真|tr=ma-|t=true}} + {{m|ja|3=つ|tr=tsu|pos=abbreviation of {{m|ja|約まる|tr=tsuzumaru|t=to shrink}}}}.
* From {{m|ja|間千|tr=machi|lit=space (of) thousands}}.
* A shift from {{m|ja|股|tr=mata|t=crouch}}, as the pine tree leaves split into two.

